task.summary:
// Second major build commit (additional screens) This materially finishes the core build of the web-app to replicate the V1.0 client app
/ Main Changes
#App:Lib Updated LoanProjection/Validator objects to use dictionaries and enhance calculations for views
#App:Views Additional forms for additional Views GiveAmount form is novel - two helpers to produce one form
#App:Urls Additional URL mapping to new Views
#Static Additional images / icons Additions to custom CSS
#Templates New Templates to support new Views Refactoring of client templates to be self contained and new sidebar component Introduction of {Script} block to include Javascript/Jquery on relevant pages JQuery to render the slider (JSON object passed) JQuery to disable radio buttons on in Results page
/ Incidental Changes
#App:Eligibility - Non-related to client app (cleaned up / consistent naming convention)
#App: Landing - Cleaned up / consistent naming convention

/ Primary Changes - PDF rendering functionality
Added separate template folder and HTML components for the PDF Document. While code is reused from the GUI version, the pdf document is rendered separately on an A4 sized page with associated CSS. The challenge here is to get the page to render properly in A4 when Bootstrap can't interpret the breakpoints (default renders as a mobile page).
PDF rendering is done via an API to api2pdf. This is not fully implemented. Some basic persistence is being achieved by pickling data to files. This is not robust/secure and a data model is required.
Separated client Application into Version 1.0 and Version 2.0. Version 1.0 is a like for like replacement of the existing App. Version 2.0 will incorporate design changes.
Some refinements of the loanProjection calculation have been made. Further refinements are required (and calcs need to be validated).
Some helper functions in Client:Views were introduced to help extract the projection points from the main projection array.
Updated and separated (fully) the css for the client web-app and the other site apps.
Updated calculation of establishment fee. Fee charged on advanced funds - not total loan amount.

// Major Update - Database Backend and Case app
1. Database - back end. Prior temporary approach of persisting data using three dictionaries (Client, Loan and Economic) saved to the session replaced. All data now saved to the postgressql backend using three models (case, loan and modellsettings) which are essentially the same as the dictionaries.
- Some of the fieldnames were changed leading to small changes in the Views, Forms and Templates
- The Django class based views handle most of the database interaction, so the View base classes were changes (Update, Create and List views) and code required to work with the dictionaries removed. This implementation is less involved than the initial.
- The loan and modelsettings models are extensions of case (one to one foreign keys) and are separated mainly for convenience.
- A custom model manager returns either a queryset (which can be updated) or a dictionary (to add to the context)
- The model is associated with the app 'case' not with 'client'
2. A new Case app has been created to manage the list of outstanding cases (leads and opportunities). This simple app is comprised of a ListView of cases and enables a user to select an individual case (Update View). From there the user can navigate to a client meeting/interface app (client). This is now the landing app of the site.
For security/navigation purposes (inadvertent navigation to another customer's information) the case app hands off to the client app via a UUID URL keyword. There is no practical way to navigate to the client app unless passed across by the case app.
3. Integration of API2PDF - the html templates used for the pdf were finalised. That URL/View is never rendered by a user and is used by the API to render the page and convert to pdf. The pdf is retrieved, stored on the app server, added to the case record and served to the browser. The API uses the UUID to access the page. Additional security (e.g., temporary UUID rather than the actual should be developed).
4. Consents - these were implemented using modals. Acceptance is recorded in the database as well as specific meeting time. The consents were also added to the Summary PDF. Consent wording is maintained in HTML template components.
5. Loan utilities - the validation and projection classes were enhanced (changing field names and error handling). These were moved out of the client app to the apps directory under a lib folder.
6. The eligibility app is still within the project folders but not reachable. Most of the functionality is now in the case app (when client details are entered). The remaining functionality will be included in Analyis functionality in case (then the app removed)
NB Deployment risk/effort has increased somewhat with the use of models. It is fine for a clean install - but making app changes with an existing database requires database migrations to be applied.
